Memory-first execution.

Here is the single design choice that makes Spark fast. Spark keeps intermediate results in executor memory, instead of writing them to disk between every step.

To see why that matters, compare it with the previous generation, Hadoop map-reduce. Map-reduce did a full disk round-trip after every stage. It wrote the intermediate output to disk, then read it back for the next step. On a pipeline with many steps, all of that disk traffic dominated the runtime.

Spark keeps the data in memory and hands it straight to the next step. Data only spills to disk when something forces it out — usually memory pressure, or an explicit checkpoint. That one decision is most of Spark's speed advantage over map-reduce.

Everything else you will learn later — caching, broadcast joins, adaptive query execution — is an optimization layered on top of this memory-first core.

There is a trade-off, of course. Memory is finite. A job that tries to hold too much will spill to local disk, and in the worst case it will fail with an out-of-memory error. Sizing your partitions so they fit comfortably in executor memory is a theme we return to when we reach performance tuning.
